# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andy-seminick
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andy-seminick/1915-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1915 throughout the world.
[src:andy-seminick/1915-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:andy-seminick/1939-new-york-giants-mlb-season] The **1939 New York Giants season** was the franchise's 57th season.
[src:andy-seminick/1939-new-york-giants-mlb-season] The team finished in fifth place in the National League with a 77–74 record, 18½ games behind the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:andy-seminick/1941-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1941 Pittsburgh Pirates** was a season in American baseball.
[src:andy-seminick/1941-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The team finished fourth in the National League with a record of 81–73, 19 games behind the first-place Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1943 throughout the world.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-in-baseball-p01] All Negro leagues standings below are per MLB and Seamheads.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-in-baseball-p01] This was the seventh season of the Negro American League.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-in-baseball-p01] Birmingham and Chicago each won a half of the season, which therefore matched them up in a matchup to determine the champion for the NAL pennant to determine who would make the 1943 Negro World Series.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-in-baseball-p01] Birmingham prevailed in five games to win their first ever pennant.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-in-baseball-p01] This was the eleventh season of the second Negro National League.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-in-baseball-p01] For the sixth time in seven seasons, the Homestead Grays won the pennant, this time under manager Candy Jim Taylor.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-in-baseball-p01] The Negro National League All Star team & Atlanta Black Crackers played against the two leagues.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-philadelphia-phillies-season] The **1943 Philadelphia Phillies season** was the 61st season in the history of the franchise.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-philadelphia-phillies-season] On March 9, Cox announced that the team would officially be called the "Phillies" again after former-President Gerald Nugent had named them "Phils" prior to the 1942 season.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-philadelphia-phillies-season] In 1943, the team rose out of the standings cellar for the first time in five years.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-philadelphia-phillies-season] The fans responded with an increase in attendance.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-philadelphia-phillies-season] Eventually, it was revealed by Cox that he had been betting on the Phillies, and he was banned from baseball.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies opened spring training on March 18 in Hershey, Pennsylvania.
[src:andy-seminick/1943-philadelphia-phillies-season] They used the baseball diamond at Hershey High School.
[src:andy-seminick/1945-philadelphia-phillies-season] The **1945 Philadelphia Phillies season** was the 63rd season in the history of the franchise.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] The **1946 Philadelphia Phillies season** was the 64th season in the history of the franchise.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies held spring training in Miami Beach, Florida, returning to Flamingo Field where the team had trained from 1940 to 1942 before World War II travel restrictions kept teams close to home.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] The team stayed at the Boulevard Hotel at the corner of Dade Boulevard and Meridian Avenue.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies held minor league camp in Dover, Delaware.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] For the first time in the 1946 season, the Philadelphia Phillies used airplanes to travel between cities during the regular season.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies chartered two planes and returned to Philadelphia from Chicago following the scheduled June 12 game against the Cubs.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] In June 1946, the Cleveland American League club was sold to Bill Veeck and a note appeared in the *Sporting News* that the team was considering a spring training move to Tucson, Arizona for 1947.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] Paul Ficht, secretary of the Clearwater Chamber of Commerce, along with Mayor J.C.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] Louis Browns, Newark Bears, Kansas City Blues, and Phillies about training in Clearwater in 1947.
[src:andy-seminick/1946-philadelphia-phillies-season] On July 27, 1946, Hendrix announced that the Phillies had accepted Clearwater's invitation to train at Clearwater Athletic Field in 1947 on a one-year agreement.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Seminick was born in Pierce, West Virginia to Lemko immigrant parents, but moved to Muse, Pennsylvania when Andy was two.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] His father was a Rusyn from Żegiestów in Nowy Sacz County.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] He was contracted as an amateur free agent in 1941 by the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Seminick led the Appalachian League in 1942 with 15 home runs and 202 total bases, and was among the league leaders in batting average.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] In 1943, he had a .303 batting average with the Knoxville Smokies of the Class-A Southern Association, and was purchased by the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] At the age of 23, Seminick made his major league debut on September 14, 1943.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] By 1945, the Phillies were using Seminick in a platoon system alongside veteran catcher Gus Mancuso.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] While he could hit for power, his defensive skills were below average, as he led the National League in errors in 1946, 1948 and 1949.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Phillies manager Eddie Sawyer assigned Phillies coach and former catcher Cy Perkins to tutor him, which helped improve his defensive skills.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] He was voted by baseball fans to be the starting catcher for the National League in the 1949 All-Star Game, mostly for his reputation as a hitter.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] On June 2, 1949, the Phillies hit five home runs during the eighth inning in a 12–3 victory over Cincinnati at Shibe Park, tying the major league mark set by the 1939 New York Giants.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Seminick hit two home runs in the inning, while Del Ennis, Willie Jones and Schoolboy Rowe had one each.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Jones added a triple as Granny Hamner's double jumped the extra bases total to 18, still a record.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Seminick collected three home runs overall.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] With his defensive and pitch calling skills improved, Seminick played an important leadership role during the 1950 "Whiz Kids" championship season.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] On August 12, 1950, in a game against the Giants, Seminick became irritated after Eddie Stanky repeatedly waved his arms while Seminick was batting.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Stanky was eventually ejected from the game, but Seminick took out his frustrations on Bill Rigney, Stanky's replacement at second base.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] After he reached base on an error in the fourth inning, he slid hard into second base, crashing into Rigney and causing him to fall over.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] A nearly ten-minute brawl erupted between the teams, which required police intervention and resulted in the ejection of Seminick and Rigney from the game.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Seminick enjoyed his best season in 1950, hitting for a .288 batting average with 24 home runs and 68 runs batted in.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Seminick broke his ankle late in the season, but continued to play with the injury until the Phillies lost to the New York Yankees in the World Series.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Future Hall of Fame pitcher, Robin Roberts said of Seminick,"If you had to pick a guy in the clubhouse who was our leader that year, it would be Andy.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] He always played hard, and that was his best year by far".
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] In 1951, Seminick was beaned by a Max Lanier fastball, diminishing his ability to play.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] He was traded to the Cincinnati Reds for catcher Smoky Burgess, playing there from 1952 until the early part of the 1955 season.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] In 1955, he was once again traded for Burgess, returning to the Phillies, where he led National League catchers with a .994 fielding percentage.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] He played two more years before ending his playing career at the age of 36 after the 1957 season.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] In a 15-year major league career, Seminick played in 1,304 games, totaling 953 hits in 3,921 at bats for a .243 batting average, with 164 home runs and 556 runs batted in.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] He threw out 44.6% of the base runners who tried steal a base on him, 16th on the all-time list.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Seminick led National League catchers twice in baserunners caught stealing and once each in putouts, assists and fielding percentage.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] At the time of his retirement, he ranked seventh all-time in home runs by catchers.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] After retiring as a player, Seminick worked for the Philadelphia organization for the rest of his life.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] After that, he served as a scout and as a roving minor-league instructor for the Phillies (1974–mid-1980s).
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Notably, ninety of the players he managed or coached eventually played in the major leagues, including Mike Schmidt, Ferguson Jenkins, Greg Luzinski and Bob Boone.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Seminick helped to convert Boone from a third baseman to one of the best defensive catchers in baseball.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] In the 1990s, Seminick served as a catching instructor for Philadelphia in spring training and in the Florida Instructional League.
[src:andy-seminick/andy-seminick] Andy Seminick died in Palm Bay, Florida, at 83 years of age.
